President Barack Obama has issued a proclamation declaring Thursday, November 24, 2011, as a National Day of Thanksgiving in the United States. In the proclamation, he highlights the significance of Thanksgiving Day as a time for families to come together and reflect on the blessings in their lives. He also acknowledges the historical roots of Thanksgiving, when the Wampanoag tribe joined the Pilgrims at Plymouth Colony to celebrate the autumn harvest. The proclamation encourages Americans to express gratitude for their loved ones, as well as to show appreciation for the contributions of American Indians and Alaska Natives to the nation's heritage. President Obama also urges people to remember the sacrifices of the men and women in uniform and to support fellow citizens in need. The proclamation emphasizes the importance of gratitude and generosity, and encourages individuals to give back to their communities.